segments.text: Are there some people out there in the state that you think deserve special credit for that support, special appreciation?
not being particularly in the know about a lot of those things.
I've always been an outsider.
We were shielded from legislation.
I think this is where the actions came.
Are you aware of some governors or politicians that were helpful?
Not particularly.
I think there's some of those that were on the legislature budget board or those that met to listen to the presentations.
Like I'm guessing Bill Moore.
Bill Moore, probably.
Bill was always a defender of and a promoter of Texas A&M.
If it was the Tittle Wings team, I think Bill would have
and our comparatively shy state representative.
No, before, earlier.
He went to our church.
He was a Presbyterian bachelor.
had an office above J.C. Penney in that, oh, what was his name?
He later became a district, I mean, adjusted the piece.
Oh, what was his name?
He was on the Appropriations Committee.
Is there any governor that was sensitive to veterinary medicine?
Briscoe, Kahn?
I would think Donald Briscoe.
Yeah, I don't think Donald Briscoe, but I don't know of any particular instances in there that, like I say,
I have claim innocence in no way.
Which presidents do you think were the most, A&M presidents, were the most concerned about vet medicine?
I never looked at the president's favorite.
I thought the person that probably did more for vet medicine than as he did for the Institutes of Reserve, really.
I just respect his attitude and what he did, even though he had opposition, and those were people who didn't want to be told anything.
Are there any special moments that you recall with joy and pride when some special something happened?
Probably when the Neopets school was open was one.
I can't think of anything.
My relationship there is one highlight.
Of all your scholarly work, what one or two publications would you point to with greatest pride?
My research was mainly diversified, very diversified.
As I tell you, the one that I was most satisfied with was one of the horses, because we did define that.
And it has an impact.
We did some other things that I think were...
This is the one about the, and the fence?
Yes.
Okay.
Where did you publish that?
Journal of American Medical Association, American Journal of Veterinary Research.
And we had other publications on national disease.
I did quite a bit on identifying new pathogens of fungi and worked with the National Institute of Health mycologists on those.
And those were enjoyable because they
new knowledge and the identification of new species, which have later been found in humans.
Some of the others are, like I say, the one on the sheep has gotten less emphasis because sheep are just not that important anymore.
And that's in some people's opinion.
But I guess the thing that I've gotten satisfaction out of in my career has been my graduate program, which we had good people that came out and are well-represented.
Which doctoral students would you point to with greatest pride?
Well, I think Gary Adams is one.
Ken Pierce.
We had others like Gwynne Allman.
Depending on accomplishments or other attention, Kirkland Kerr.
Kerr, K-E-R-R.
He went to LSU, didn't he?
No, no.
Well, he went to LSU, but then he went on.
He's ill.
All right, let's make believe that you... Who's that?
Oh, Roger is one of your graduate students?
Mm-hmm.
Let's make believe that you've now just been hired as a consultant to give advice today to the Dean of Veterinary Medicine at Texas A&M.
What advice would you give the Dean of Veterinary Medicine today?
The Dean of Veterinary Medicine has to work on, it's fairly cool, for the faculty, individual faculty member, that he knows that that faculty member needs to excel
for his own good and academically, which means being a scholar and being a good teacher.
And then he should organize so he can promote that.
And I think that I've got a lot of thanks for that.
What are you going to tell him then?
We just funded a chair in medical education.
What they proposed may not be what I want to see.
I would like to see a situation where a teacher can teach and a student comes to him wanting knowledge, but he does not have to quiz that student.
by challenging them, but they can work together to accomplish this.
Now, I know that's contrary to the great authoritarian power of the faculty member.
But to me, it would be just a wonderful experience to be in a situation where a student comes to you, and he wants you.
I don't understand this.
And you feel like you can talk to him.
Whether we're not worried about giving them the answer to the question you're going to ask.
Sounds like a good plan to me.
Yeah.
I would love to see that.
And that's what they're fortunate with this, is it'll work with young faculty.
That was the advice for the department.
No, that was for the dean.
For the dean.
OK. Now, what advice would you give to the department?
Or an apartment head?
Either way.
Well, I think that each faculty member needs an apartment head that nobody respects.
And I always had this philosophy, and I think I got this, I guess, from the years of Earl Broder.
His philosophy was...
I propose a raise for this person or a promotion and his answer would be, you hired this person and he told me he was a good teacher, he's going to be an excellent person.
He's a leader in his field and we paid, set a budget to pay him for this and we're paying him for that.
What has he done now?
to warrant this.
Tell me.
Don't tell me again he's a good teacher.
And I feel like that if department heads could approach the thing, what can I do for you today?
And if I go as your representative to the dean, what can I tell the dean that you're done?
Now, were you a believer in merit salary?
Oh, yes.
And I believe in demerit salaries.
Because I think that there is such a thing that faculty members take, some faculty members take a job, this is mine, I'm going to do this, and they'll say, this is an opportunity for me.
And those that want a position
And there's one thing, a difference from those who want opportunity.
And I think that needs to be conveyed to the faculty by the department heads in such a way.
And I think one of the problems is that people are hired now not knowing that they may want to expect it at a certain time because nobody says so.
Now one of my standard questions at this point, you've just answered in an unusual way.
Normally I say, if you could make a very significant gift to Texas A&M, what would it be for?
And you've already, yeah.
Has that been announced?
Okay.
I think it has.
It's been in the veterinary thing.
Okay.
Okay.
I think the...
Foundation is going to have it in their magazine.
Right then, I have only two other questions.
What does it mean to be a Texas Aggie?
What is special about being a product of this institution?
I have to say I'm proud to be a Texas Aggie.
For a long time, I didn't know what it meant to be a Texan Aggie.
I was a graduate of this institute.
I got a degree.
I'm going out and conquering the world or whatever.
And I had a little office over in Brennan.
I'm old.
A little bit emotional, but Hugh Miller used to come to me, sit in my office and talk to me.
He didn't talk about the Aggies, are we going to win, or that.
He just was interested in what was going on.
He was a good neighbor.
And I had other people that do the same thing.
Charlie Rankin used to come by.
He was, I never knew that the Aggies were supposed to be important to each other.
We're supposed to be what?
Important to each other.
Oh.
Significant.
And I just, it wasn't engendered in me because I'd gone through work.
I guess because I wasn't a member of the Corps.
I lived in the unit.
My background is a little different, I can say.
Sometimes I'm almost embarrassed.
But...
Yeah, I'm proud to be an Aggie.
All right, then the last question is a follow-up on that.
What feelings do you have in your heart about A&M today?
I believe in education.
I believe in the learning process.
And Mildred's going to get mad at me if I say it.
I believe in God.
God and the church.
division organization has killed a lot of the spirit and in
And that, I guess, is way over.
But we always second-guess other people's behaviors, and that's probably one of them.
Let me ask you something else.
You said when he retired, but he just stepped down.
Oh.
And then stayed.
When did you retire then?
In 86 first and then I went half time and continued my research and then I spent some time, went to New Zealand and lectured and a few things like that.
So you served a total of how many years?
Oh, I guess to the 80th.
I was
I think the record says 54.
It was a period of time, a few months in there, that I served as an interim basis.
But I would say 54 to 88.
Have we left out anything important that you want to be sure to include?
All right, well, let's quit at that.
